    <main>
        <article id="intro">
            <h2>What is Semantic HTML?</h2>
            <p>Semantic HTML means using HTML tags that accurately describe the content they contain. Instead of using generic <span> and <div> tags, we use descriptive tags like &lt;header&gt;, &lt;article&gt;, and &lt;footer&gt;. This practice improves both accessibility and SEO.</p>
        </article>
        
        <article id="core-concepts">
            <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
            
            <section>
                <h3>For Accessibility</h3>
                <p>Screen readers use semantic tags as landmarks to help users navigate the page efficiently. A user can easily jump from the header to the main content or the footer.</p>
            </section>
            
            <section>
                <h3>For SEO</h3>
                <p>Search engines like Google understand the structure of your page better when you use semantic tags. It helps them identify the most important content, which can improve your search ranking.</p>
                
                <figure>
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200" alt="A diagram showing the structure of an HTML5 semantic page.">
                    <figcaption>Fig. 1 - A basic layout using semantic tags.</figcaption>
                </figure>
            </section>
        </article>
        
        <aside>
            <h2>Did You Know?</h2>
            <p>HTML5 introduced over 20 new semantic elements, making the web more structured and meaningful than ever before.</p>
        </aside>
    </main>

